Genre: Puzzle Game
Goal: Control light sources to cast shadows and create paths.
Graphics API: Vulkan
Game Idea and Content
Story: In a world where light shapes reality, you play as an explorer trapped inside an ancient
temple filled with mysterious mechanisms. The temple reacts to light, shifting walls, platforms,
and hidden passages based on the placement of glowing orbs. To escape, you must master the
art of casting and blocking light, revealing the path forward. Will you uncover the temple’s secret
before darkness consumes you?
Gameplay: Players can place and move light sources to illuminate areas, activate doors, and
manipulate shadows as physical objects. Shadows cast on certain surfaces create temporary
platforms, bridges, or barriers. Some puzzles require blocking or redirecting light using objects,
mirrors, or rotating walls. The goal of each level is to reach the exit by carefully adjusting the
light and shadows in the environment.
User Interaction:
• WASD: Move the character
• Mouse: Adjust camera view
• LMB: Pick up/place light sources or objects
• RMB: Rotate objects (mirrors, reflectors, barriers)
• Space: Jump
• E: Interact with puzzle elements (turn the light source on and off)
• ESC: Settings menu
Effects
Gameplay:
Mandatory:
● 3D Geometry (6 points): Detailed temple environments, walls, platforms, and
interactive objects.
● Playable (3 points): The player can move around the world, interact with objects,
and solve puzzles.
● Min 60 FPS and Framerate Independence (3 points): The rendering pipeline will
be optimized to maintain at least 60 FPS with smooth gameplay.
● Win/Lose Condition (3 points): Players win by solving puzzles and reaching the
exit; they lose if they fall into pits or fail timed challenges.
● Intuitive controls (2 points): The controls are simple: WASD for movement,
mouse for camera, E for interaction, and LMB/RMB for object placement and
interaction.
● Intuitive Camera (2 points): The camera smoothly follows player movement with
adjustable sensitivity.
● Illumination model (2 points): The game uses a physically-based illumination
model to create realistic lighting and shadow effects.
● Textures (2 points): Textures will be applied to surfaces, including walls, floors,
and interactive objects, to enhance realism.
● Moving Objects (2 points): Mirrors, rotating panels, and objects can be moved to
change the light’s path and solve puzzles.
● Documentation (1 points): The project will include a short document describing
game mechanics, controls, and technical implementation.
● Adjustable Parameters (1 point): Players can adjust brightness, shadow
sharpness, and mouse sensitivity in settings.
Optional:
● Advanced Gameplay (5 points): The game includes multi-layered puzzles that
require sequential interactions, time-based challenges, and progressive difficulty.
● Collision Detection (Basic Physics) (6 points): Objects will have collision
physics to prevent walking through walls and allow realistic placement of light
sources.
● Heads-up Display (4 points): A simple UI will display active light sources, level
progress, and key hints.
Effects:
Lighting:
● Shadow Map with PCF (16 Points): The game will implement Percentage-Closer
Filtering (PCF) shadow mapping to create smooth, realistic shadows from light
sources.
Advanced Modelling:
● CPU Particle System (8 Points): A simple CPU-based particle system will be
used for dust and light effects in the environment.
Shading:
● Simple Normal Mapping (4 Points): Normal maps will be used to enhance
surface details of walls and floors.